text:
Compared to previous study of earlier the same day. 
CLINICAL INDICATION: PICC line placement. 
A right sided PICC line has been removed, a left PICC line has been placed, and forces into the left side of the neck. A tracheostomy tube and nasogastric tube remain in place. Pleural and parenchymal abnormalities described on the earlier radiograph of the same day are unchanged in the interval. 
IMPRESSION: Malpositioned left PICC line extending into the left side of the neck as communicated with the IV nurse caring for the patient.

INDICATION:  Right IJ line placement. 
CHEST AP:  Comparison is made to the prior film dated [**2131-5-9**].  There is interval placement of a right-sided IJ central line, with the tip not well visualized, but most likely within the SVC.  No evidence of pneumothorax. Again noted is ET tube, which is in good position.  There has been interval removal of Swan-Ganz catheter.  NG tube is extending toward the abdomen.  No evidence of pneumothorax.  Again noted is evidence of bilateral patchy opacities, consistent with ARDS.  This remain unchanged from the prior exam. 
IMPRESSION:  1)  Interval placement of a right IJ central line, with the tip not well visualized, but most likely in SVC.  No evidence of pneumothorax. 
2)  Persistent bilateral patchy opacities, consistent with ARDS.

HISTORY:  Pain following MCC.  Assess for fracture. 
MANDIBLE, FOUR VIEWS:  No Panorex view obtained.  The site of symptoms is not indicated.  A collar is in place, which likely limits positioning. 
No displaced mandibular fracture is identified.  Assessment of the TM joints is not optimal on these views, but no gross derangement is identified on the right side.  The left side is only seen on the frontal view due to positioning. 
IMPRESSION:  No obvious mandibular fracture or TMJ dislocation.  However, the left TM joint is not optimally visualized, and if clinical suspicion remains high, then further assessment with CT would be recommended.

INDICATION:  Feeding tube needed for nutrition, patient with cervical fracture. 
NASOINTESTINAL TUBE PLACEMENT:  The left naris was anesthetized with lidocaine jelly.  An 8 French [**Location (un) 1213**]-[**Doctor First Name 948**] feeding tube was advanced until the tip reached the second portion of the duodenum.  Attempts were made to position the tip further toward the ligament of Treitz; however, this proved unsuccessful.  An injection of Conray confirms tube placement into the second portion of the duodenum. 
IMPRESSION:  Successful placement of an 8 French [**Location (un) 1213**]-[**Doctor First Name 948**] feeding tube into the second portion of the duodenum.  The tube is ready to use.

HISTORY:  Status post endotracheal tube placement. 
COMPARISON:  [**2118-6-5**]. 
FINDINGS:  AP portable supine view.  The endotracheal tube terminates in good position, approximately 3 cm above the carina.  The nasogastric tube makes a loop within the patient's hiatal hernia and turns back up, terminating in the mid-esophagus.  This was discussed with Dr. [**Last Name (STitle) 13149**] at 5:05 p.m. on [**2118-6-7**]. 
The heart, mediastinum and pulmonary vessels appear normal.  The lung parenchyma is clear.  There is no pleural effusion.  The visualized osseous structures are grossly unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION: 1.  Satisfactory position of the endotracheal tube. 2.  Malposition of the nasogastric tube.

20-year-old female after motor vehicle collision with pneumothorax, referred for evaluation of interval change. 
COMPARISON:  [**2143-7-2**] at 5:47 a.m. 
AP SUPINE PORTABLE CHEST:  There has been no significant interval change in a small left apical pneumothorax.  The left subclavian central catheter, endotracheal tube, and nasogastric tube, are in unchanged positions. The sidehole of the nasogastric tube remains above the diaphragm.  The heart size and cardiomediastinal contours are within normal limits.  The lung fields are grossly clear and there is no pleural effusion or focal consolidation.  The surrounding osseous and soft tissue structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION:  No interval change in small left apical pneumothorax. Nasogastric tube sidehole above the diaphragm and advancement approximately 5 cm is suggested.

PORTABLE CHEST: 
CLINICAL INDICATION:  Increasing oxygen requirement and shortness of breath. 
Comparison is made to previous study of one day earlier. 
The patient is s/p median sternotomy and coronary artery bypass surgery.  The cardiac and mediastinal contours are stable in the interval.  The pulmonary vascularity is normal.  There are patchy and linear opacities in the mid and lower lung zones which have slightly worsened in the interval in the right mid and left lower lung zones.  Small pleural effusions are seen bilaterally.  No pneumothorax is identified. 
IMPRESSION:  Slight worsening of mid and lower lung zone opacities, most likely due to atelectasis.  Differential diagnosis for the more confluent areas of opacity at the bases includes aspiration and pneumonia. 
Small bilateral pleural effusions.

INDICATION: New onset right hemiparesis and aphasia with status post TPA. 
COMPARISON: MRI of same day. 
TECHNIQUE: CT of the head without IV contrast. 
FINDINGS: There are no intra or extraaxial hemorrhage, edema, or shift of normal midline structures. The ventricles are symmetric in size. There is tortuousity of the vertebral and basilar arteries as was seen on the MRA. 
White matter hypodensity and volume loss are seen, and reflect microvascular ischemia and infarction.  An acute infarction may be difficult to discern, given the gliotic changes. Overall cortical density appears to be preserved. 
BONE WINDOWS: There are no suspicious osseous lesions. 
IMPRESSION: No evidence of acute intracranial hemorrhage.

INDICATION:  Intracranial hemorrhage, intubated. 
COMPARISON:  None. 
TECHNIQUE:  AP portable supine chest (two radiographs). 
FINDINGS:  The heart size is upper limits of normal.  There is tortuosity of the aorta.  Dense opacity within the left retrocardiac region consistent with left lower lobe atelectasis and consolidation.  Plate like atelectasis at the right base.  No definite pleural effusion or pneumothorax is identified.  The patient is status post right humeral head prosthesis, and there is severe degenerative changes at the shoulder joints bilaterally.  An endotracheal tube is in place with tip terminating approximately 3.5 cm from the carina. 
Severe degenerative changes and right convex lumbar scoliosis are visualized. 
IMPRESSION: 
1.  Status post endotracheal intubation, with tube tip terminating 3.5 cm from the carina. 
2.  Left lower lobe consolidation and collapse.  Plate like atelectasis at the right base.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Right thyroid nodule.  History of recent pancreatic carcinoma. 
THYROID BIOPSY 
Initial ultrasound shows a normal left lobe and isthmus. 
Occupying the majority of the right lobe is a nodule that measures 5.1 x 2.8 x 2.5 cm.  This nodule is isoechoic and shows some echogenic foci, some with shadowing, some with comet tailing.  The nodule has modest vascularity. 
These findings were explained to the patient and fine needle aspiration recommended.  Written informed consent was obtained and a formal timeout was taken. 
Local anesthesia was administered and under direct ultrasonic guidance, four fine needle aspirations of the right thyroid nodule were made.  There were no immediate complications. 
IMPRESSION:  Fine needle aspiration of right thyroid nodule.

HISTORY:  84-year-old man status post MCA stroke, CHF, recent extubation, requiring NG tube, evaluate for NG tube placement. 
TECHNIQUE:  A supine portable chest x-ray dated [**2110-5-10**] at 10:23 a.m. was obtained.  Comparison is made to a prior chest x-ray dated [**2110-5-8**]. 
FINDINGS:  There has been interval removal of the endotracheal tube and orogastric tube.  Note is now made of a new nasogastric tube with its tip in the expected location of the stomach. 
There is blunting of the right costophrenic angle which appears new since the prior chest x-ray dated [**2110-5-8**], consistent with a small right pleural effusion.  The left lung is incompletely seen on this x- ray. 
IMPRESSION:  Tip of the NG tube is in the expected location of the stomach.

PORTABLE CHEST: 
CLINICAL INDICATION:   Right pig-tail catheter placement. 
Since the recent study, a right pig-tail pleural catheter has been placed, with associated resolution of a previously noted large right pleural effusion.  No definite pneumothorax is identified on this supine radiograph.  However, the right hemidiaphragms appear sharper than the left and is difficult to exclude a basilar pneumothorax as a cause of this finding.  A Swan-Ganz catheter remains in the right ventricular outflow tract, and a left subclavian vascular catheter and nasogastric tube remain in satisfactory position.  An endotracheal tube terminates at the thoracic inlet level.  Minor atelectatic changes are noted at the left base. 
IMPRESSION: 
Resolution of right pleural effusion following right sided chest tube placement.  It is difficult to exclude a basilar pneumothorax on this supine radiograph as detailed above.

INDICATION: 74 y/o woman with hypotension, shortness of breath and diminished breath sounds. 
COMPARISON: [**2116-3-2**] AP portable. 
AP PORTABLE SUPINE RADIOGRAPH OF THE CHEST: There is stable cardiomegaly. The mediastinal and hilar contours are unchanged in appearance. There are bilateral layering pleural effusions. The bilateral perihilar haziness and patchy opacities could be partially due to patient positioning. ETT is seen approximately 3 cm above the carina. A left subclavian line is seen with its tip at the junction of the brachiocephalic and SVC. Soft tissue and osseous structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION: 1) Bilateral layering pleural effusions. 2) Although the bilateral patchy opacities may be partially due to supine positioning, an element of ARDS vs. aspiration pneumonia/multifocal pneumonia cannot be excluded.

HEAD ULTRASOUND: 
HISTORY:  This is a 29 [**5-11**] week premature infant, now 27 days old.  He has had previous intraventricular hemorrhage with enlarged ventricles.  This examination is compared to prior head ultrasound studies, dating from [**2198-11-2**] to the most recent previous study dated [**2198-10-26**].  The infant has developed post hemorrhagic hydrocephalus. 
When compared to the most recent prior study, there is slight decrease in ventricular size.  There is still moderate ventriculomegaly with a retracting clot in both lateral ventricles.  The anterior cerebral artery Doppler shows a resistive index of .81.  Compression was not applied.  There are no new areas of hemorrhage. 
IMPRESSION:  Evolving post hemorrhagic hydrocephalus.  The ventricles continue to diminish slightly in size when compared to the most recent prior study dated [**2198-10-26**].

HISTORY:  56-year-old male with new PICC. 
COMPARISON:  [**2186-12-14**]. 
FINDINGS:  Portable upright frontal chest radiograph demonstrates interval placement of a left upper extremity PICC, the tip of which projects over the upper SVC.  Multiple blebs are again noted in the peripheral right upper lung, better seen on CT from [**2186-6-23**].  The cardiac silhouette is top normal in size, accentuated by portable technique.  The pulmonary vasculature appears mildly engorged.  There is no pleural effusion or pneumothorax.  The mediastinal contours are normal. 
IMPRESSION: 1.  Interval placement of left upper extremity PICC, the tip of which is in the upper SVC. 
2.  Interval decrease in heart size from [**2186-11-19**]; the pulmonary vasculature is minimally engorged.

SINGLE VIEW OF THE CHEST, [**2201-2-21**]. 
HISTORY:  89-year-old female with CHF and increasing dyspnea. 
FINDINGS:  Single bedside AP examination labeled "upright at 17:25" is compared with remote two-view study, dated [**2197-6-18**]; the overall appearance is not much changed.  There is minimal bibasilar subsegmental atelectasis or scarring.  No focal airspace process is seen.  The heart is unchanged in size, with no significant pulmonary vascular congestion, pleural effusion or other evidence of CHF.  There are atherosclerotic changes involving the thoracic aorta.  A probable tiny granuloma projects over the lateral aspect of the right second rib. 
IMPRESSION:  No acute process; specifically, there is no evidence of significant CHF.

REASON FOR EXAMINATION:  Followup of a patient with thoracic aortic dissection and abdominal aortic aneurysm. 
Portable chest radiograph compared to [**2192-9-16**] obtained at 03:24 a.m. 
The ET tube is 6.5 cm above the carina.  The NG tube tip passes below the diaphragm, most likely terminating in the stomach.  The right subclavian line tip is in the mid SVC. 
There is no change in the heart size.  Distended thoracic aorta is again noted.  There is bilateral pleural effusion, moderate, right more than left, slightly increased.  There is unchanged appearance of stented aorta. 
IMPRESSION:  Mild pulmonary edema and bilateral increased pleural effusions, partially loculated on the left.

CT HEAD 
INDICATION:  Bilateral subarachnoid hemorrhage. 
COMPARISON:  CT head dated [**2175-7-15**] and [**2175-7-17**]. 
TECHNIQUE:  Non-contrast head CT. 
FINDINGS:  There is continued interval decreased conspicuity of the previously identified bilateral areas of subarachnoid hemorrhage.  No new areas of intracranial hemorrhage are identified.  Minimal, if any, leftward shift of midline structures remains.  The ventricles, sulci, and cisterns are stable in appearance.  The appearance of the brain parenchyma is unchanged.  Small left scalp hematoma continues to resolve.  The visualized paranasal sinuses and osseous structures are stable. 
IMPRESSION:  Continued decreased conspicuity of bilateral subarachnoid hemorrhage with no new areas of hemorrhage or mass effect identified. 
NOTE ADDED AT ATTENDING REVIEW: There is no evidence of midline shift. There is no evidence of mass effect.

INDICATION:  Left foot pain in patient with limited mobility. 
COMPARISON:  Radiographs of the knee and ankle from [**2112-1-24**]. 
LEFT KNEE AND ANKLE, SIX VIEWS: 
LEFT ANKLE:  The study is essentially unchanged from the prior examination. There is no fracture or dislocation.  Soft tissues are unremarkable.  An old fracture of the medial malleolus is unchanged from the prior examination.  The ankle mortise is intact.  There are no marked degenerative or erosive changes. 
LEFT KNEE:  There is no fracture or dislocation.  There are no degenerative or erosive changes.  Soft tissues are unremarkable.  A well-corticated lucency in the proximal fibula is likely a nutrient vessel, but could represent remote history of traumatic injury. 
IMPRESSION:  No acute fracture or dislocation in the left knee or ankle.

HISTORY:  Assess for acute pneumonia and CHF in a patient with history of COPD, pulmonary eosinophilia and purulent sputum. 
PA AND LATERAL CHEST RADIOGRAPHS 
Comparison is made to [**2139-7-25**] chest radiograph and [**2139-7-26**] CT 
The lungs remain clear, with unchanged biapical scarring and calcified granulomas, predominantly within the right lung.  Cardiomediastinal silhouette with pectus deformity, hilar contours, and pleural surfaces are stable as is  calcification within a slightly tortuous thoracic aorta. Hyperinflation in the lungs, and flattening of the diaphragms is noted. Heart size remains top normal. 
IMPRESSION: 
Emphysema without acute infiltrate identified.

[**2158-4-3**] CHEST 
INDICATION:  Status-post repair of tracheal tear. 
FINDINGS:  A single AP supine view. Comparison study taken [**2158-4-3**]. An endotracheal tube and an NG line are noted, both in good position. The heart and pulmonary vessels are unremarkable. The lungs appear fairly well inflated. Some minor ill-defined infiltrates are noted in the left mid-zone and there is some minor atelectasis at the left costophrenic angle. Otherwise, the lungs are clear. No pleural effusions are identified. There is no evidence of a pneumothorax. Traces of surgical emphysema are noted in the soft tissues of the neck bilaterally. 
IMPRESSION:   Minimal residual infiltrate and atelectasis in the left lung. Appearances otherwise satisfactory. The lines remain in good position. A left IJ introducer sheath is noted. 
No new cardiopulmonary abnormalities identified. Post-operative appearances are stable.

INDICATIONS:  Labored breathing. Endotracheal tube placement. 
Comparison is made to previous films from  one day earlier. 
An endotracheal tube has been placed, in satisfactory position.  A nasogastric tube courses below the diaphragms and the right PICC line remains in place. The examination of the cardiovascular status of the patient is limited due to low lung volumes and respiratory motion. With this limitation in mind there is no gross evidence of pulmonary edema.  Left retrocardiac opacity persists, unchanged.  Again demonstrated are somewhat distended loops of bowel within the imaged portion of the upper abdomen. 
IMPRESSION:   Endotracheal tube in satisfactory position. Otherwise no significant change allowing for differences in technique between the two studies.

INDICATION:  Chest pain with baseline back pain and recent stent placement. 
Comparison is made to chest x-ray dated [**2152-9-15**]. 
FINDINGS:  SINGLE AP VIEW OF THE CHEST reveals multiple rounded opacities overlying the periphery of the lungs.  These are unchanged from the prior exam.  In this upright study, the cardiomediastinal silhouette is unremarkable.  There is elevation of the right hemidiaphragm, with obscuration of the right costophrenic angle. There is no consolidation or pneumothorax identified. 
IMPRESSION: 
1. No significant interval change from prior study. 
2. Multiple opacities overlying the peripheral lung fields, which may represent calcified pleural plaques.  Follow up with PA and lateral chest x- rays is recommended.

Two view chest [**2137-11-4**] compared to previous study of [**2136-12-26**]. 
CLINICAL INDICATION:  Amiodarone therapy. 
The heart is upper limits of normal in size with left ventricular configuration.  The aorta is tortuous and the pulmonary vascularity is normal.  An ICD remains in place with leads in the right atrium and right ventricle. There is a very subtle interstitial pattern with a basilar predominance, characterized by coarse reticulation.  This appears more conspicuous than on the previous study.  No confluent areas of consolidation are seen in either lung and there are no pleural effusions.  Degenerative changes are observed in the spine. 
IMPRESSION:  Subtle basilar interstitial disease, for which amiodarone lung toxicity should be considered.  Correlative high resolution CT imaging may be helpful if warranted clinically.

INDICATION:  58-year-old male with chronic leg edema, right greater than left. Patient is wheelchair bound.  Please evaluate for deep vein thrombosis. 
FINDINGS:  Grayscale, color and pulse wave Doppler son[**Name (NI) 424**] were performed on the right common femoral, superficial femoral, and popliteal veins.  Normal flow, waveforms, compressibility and augmentation are demonstrated.  No intraluminal thrombus is identified.  Incidental note made of marked edema in the right lower extremity, most severe in the calf region. 
IMPRESSION:  No evidence of deep venous thrombosis in the right lower extremity.

INDICATION:  Back pain and radiculopathy. 
TECHNIQUE:  T1 and T2 sagittal T2 axial images of the lumbar spine. 
FINDINGS:  From T10-11 to L3-4 no abnormalities are identified. 
At L4-5 and L5-S1 levels mild disc bulging is seen without spinal stenosis, or foraminal compromise. The distal spinal cord  shows normal signal intensities. 
There is mild prominence of retroperitoneal lymph nodes in the region of aortic bifurcation.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  Abdominal CT would be helpful for further evaluation if indicated. 
IMPRESSION:  Mild disc bulging at L4-5 and L5-S1 levels. Mild prominence of retroperitoneal lymph nodes at the region at the level of the aortic bifurcation. Clinical correlation is recommended. If further evaluation is indicated, CT of the abdomen would be helpful.

HISTORY:   Hypoxia, thoracentesis. 
AP CHEST:  Compared with 1 day prior, there is significant decrease in the right pleural effusion with reexpansion of the right lung.  However, a consolidation remains in the right lower lobe, which may represent reexpansion pulmonary edema vs. residual atelectasis.  The left pleural effusion appears to have increased in size.  There is also left lower lobe collapse/consolidation.  No pneumothorax is identified on this single view. 
IMPRESSION: 
Interval decrease in size of right pleural effusion after thoracentesis. However, the left pleural effusion appears to have increased.  Persistent left lower lobe collapse/consolidation.

INDICATION: ARDS with gram positive cocci in sputum. 
Comparison made to [**2157-7-28**] at 06:51. 
PORTABLE CHEST RADIOGRAPH: ETT, right sided central venous line, and NG tube all unchanged. 
A loculated right sided pleural effusion is slightly decreased in prominence and size. There is interval decrease in the prominence of the focal right upper lobe consolidation. Patchy air space disease remains in both lungs and there is continued blunting of both costophrenic angles. Air is seen within the stomach. 
IMPRESSION: 1) Increased aeration of the right upper lung zone. Continued multifocal air space disease consistent with ARDS, essentially unchanged from study of [**7-27**].

RADIOGRAPH OF BOTH FEMORA 
INDICATION:  73-year-old woman with bilateral periprosthetic fractures status post ORIF. 
COMPARISON:  [**2175-2-14**]. 
FINDINGS:  Seven images of both femora demonstrate the patient to be ORIF bilateral periprosthetic fractures of both femora.  On the right femur there is displacement of the distal fragment, unchanged when compared to prior study. Remodeling of the right acetabulum and superior migration of the left femur is again noted and unchanged.  Vascular calcifications are again noted. Equivocal evidence of old trauma involving the left inferior and superior pubic rami is noted. 
IMPRESSION:  Status post ORIF bilateral periprosthetic fractures of the femoral diaphysis.

AP PORTABLE CHEST, [**2165-8-2**] AT 2101 
HISTORY:  Subarachnoid hemorrhage.  Intubated. 
COMPARISON:  None. 
FINDINGS:  The patient is rotated.  Lung volumes are profoundly diminished. An endotracheal tube is noted with the distal tip approximately 2.1 cm from the carina.  A nasogastric tube is also noted with the distal tip extending into the left upper quadrant and the sidehole projecting within the expected gastric body.  Subtle consolidation is evident at the right lung base.  More linear retrocardiac opacity is noted on the left.  Aortic tortuosity is noted. The cardiac silhouette size is difficult to assess but presumably is likely within normal limits for size.  No definite effusion or pneumothorax is noted on this supine radiograph. 
IMPRESSION:  Limitations as above.  There is a subtle consolidation at the right lung base, which may represent aspiration or pneumonia given the clinical context.

PA AND LATERAL CHEST [**2170-5-10**] AT 2122 HOURS. 
HISTORY:  History of CHF and atrial fibrillation, presenting with two-week history of diarrhea and cramping. 
COMPARISON:  Multiple priors, the most recent dated [**2170-4-9**]. 
FINDINGS:  There is improved aeration of the retrocardiac left lower lobe relative to the prior exam.  No consolidation or edema is evident.  The mediastinum again demonstrates calcified plaque at the aortic arch.  The cardiac silhouette remains borderline enlarged but stable.  There is mitral annulus calcification incidentally noted.  Blunting of the left costophrenic angle is again noted and relatively stable.  No large effusion is noted. There is no pneumothorax.  The osseous structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION:  Improved aeration of the left lower lobe.  No definite acute pulmonary process identified.

HISTORY:  44-year-old man with AMS, intubated.  Radiograph done to evaluate the placement of the endotracheal tube. 
TECHNIQUE:  Portable chest radiograph, single view. 
COMPARISON:  Compared to chest radiograph, [**2190-6-6**]. 
FINDINGS:  There is a new endotracheal tube, with tip at the entrance of the right main stem bronchus.  An NG tube is seen with tip coiled in the stomach. There are low lung volumes with new patchy opacity at the left lung base concerning for aspiration. Low lung volumes. There is no pleural effusion or pneumothorax. 
IMPRESSION: 1.  Malpositioned endotracheal tube, with tip at the entrance of the right main bronchus. Recomnend retraction. NG tube coiled in the stomach. 2.  Left basilar opacity, new, concerning for aspiration. 
Findings regarding the endotracheal tube was discussed with [**First Name8 (NamePattern2) 943**] [**Last Name (NamePattern1) 3218**], [**First Name3 (LF) **] at 3:15 p.m. on [**2190-6-12**].

(REVISED) INDICATION:  Subarachnoid hemorrhage right frontal lobe. 
COMPARISON:  Twelve hours prior. 
FINDINGS:  There is once again demonstrated a small amount of subarachnoid hemorrhage within the right inferior frontal lobe.  No new areas of hemorrhage are seen.  There is no mass effect, shift of normally midline structures, or hydrocephalus.  A small amount of fluid is again noted within the sphenoid sinus. 
IMPRESSION:  Right inferior frontal lobe subarachnoid hemorrhage slightly more noticeable than on the prior study, but not substantially increased in size. Lucency noted in the left frontal bone (series 3/image 25), most probably venous channnel.

HISTORY: 58-year-old woman status post fall with known C4 fracture. 
TECHNIQUE: Multiple axial images of the cervical spine were obtained without IV contrast. Reconstructions were then obtained. 
FINDINGS: There is a small chip fracture of the inferior-anterior portion of the C4 vertebral body. The small fragment is minimally displaced anteriorly. No other fractures or dislocations are identified. 
Soft tissue windows demonstrate no significant abnormalities. There is no cord compression. The lung apices demonstrate pleural thickening at the right apex; there is a small cavity seen at the right apex, which is incompletely imaged on this study. There are small bullae seen at the left lung apex. 
IMPRESSION: Minimally displaced fracture of inferior endplate anteriorly of C4. No other fractures or dislocations identified.

INDICATION:  77 y/o man with right sided effusion.  Query mass, assess ET tube position. 
PORTABLE CHEST AP VIEW:  Right sided pleural effusion is seen.  There is a mass in the right hilar region with associated right lower lobe atelectasis. The left lung field appears clear.  There is no evidence of pneumothorax. 
The Swan-Ganz catheter appears to take a left sided course and is probably located in the left sided SVC. 
IMPRESSION: 
1)  Mass in the right hilar region with associated right lower lobe atelectasis.  Moderate right sided effusion is seen. 2)  Tip of the SGC is in the left sided SVC.

INDICATION:  44-year-old male, status post intubation for respiratory arrest. 
COMPARISON:  [**2199-12-3**] at 00:38 hours. 
SEMI-UPRIGHT PORTABLE CHEST: 
Endotracheal tube is well positioned 6 cm above the carina.  There is a right PICC, extending to the low SVC.  A nasogastric feeding tube courses into the stomach, the tip off the inferior margin of the image. 
There is right perihilar and left basilar atelectasis, without focal consolidation to suggest pneumonia.  There is no pulmonary vascular congestion or edema.  There is no pleural effusion or pneumothorax.  The hilar and cardiomediastinal contours remain unremarkable, and the pleural surfaces smooth. 
IMPRESSION:  No significant change from 10 hours prior.  Persistent basilar atelectasis, without evidence of pneumonia or pulmonary edema.

INDICATION:  Abdominal pain, leukocytosis. 
COMPARISON:  Chest x-ray from two hours earlier. 
SINGLE PORTABLE AP UPRIGHT CHEST RADIOGRAPH:  The aorta is tortuous as are the vessels of the head and neck; there is likely an aberrant right subclavian artery. The heart demonstratres mild cardiomegaly. Pulmonary vasculature appears unchanged. There are bibasilar opacities, appearing similar as compared to the prior study. There may be blunting of both costophrenic angles.  No pneumothoraces are clearly identified. 
IMPRESSION:  Likely bibasilar atelectasis, although early pneumonia cannot be excluded.  Probable small bilateral pleural effusions.

INDICATION:  Status post coronary bypass surgery. 
Compared to previous study of two days earlier. 
The patient has undergone median sternotomy and coronary bypass surgery since the previous study.  There is interval slight increase in cardiac and mediastinal contours, likely due to postoperative change and supine positioning.  There has been interval development of left basilar atelectasis, predominantly in the retrocardiac region.  There is also a small left pleural effusion.  No pneumothorax is evident on this supine film, but the right CP angle has been excluded from the study and cannot be assessed. 
A SG catheter is noted, terminating in the min pulmonary artery. 
IMPRESSION:  Left lower lobe atelectasis and small left pleural effusion, status post coronary bypass surgery.

INDICATION:  Shortness of breath with diffuse crackles, intubated, rule out failure and check tube placement. 
COMPARISON: AP upright [**2139-11-13**]. 
SINGLE AP PORTABLE CHEST: Endotracheal tube noted with its tip at the level of the clavicular heads.  NG tube identified, with its tip in the mid stomach. There is severe, bilateral air-space consolidation, which could be consistent with either congestive heart failure, or diffuse pneumonia.  Moderate cardiomegaly.  Blunting of the left costophrenic angle, suggesting small effusion.  Calcified mitral annulus.  Unchanged appearance of thoracic compression fracture.  Other visualized osseous structures are unremarkable. 
IMPRESSION: 1) Severe, diffuse bilateral air-space consolidation, likely consistent with acute pulmonary edema, however, infectious cause cannot be excluded. Follow- up films recommended. 2) ETT and NG tube in satisfactory position.

INDICATION:  Evaluate ETT placement. 
PORTABLE AP CHEST X-RAY:  Comparison made to study from [**2109-9-4**].  Again seen is an ETT unchanged in position.  NGT is seen with the tip not visualized extending below the inferior margin of the image field.  There is no change in the right upper lobe and left lung field appearances.  Partial aeration of the right upper lung zone is seen and unchanged.  The diffuse patchy opacity seen in the left lung fields are unchanged from the previous exam.  Previously noted patchy infiltrate in the left cardiophrenic angle is again seen. 
IMPRESSION:  No interval change from previous exam.  NGT tip is not visualized.

INDICATION:  84-year-old female with known tracheoesophageal fistula status post Y stent of the trachea, postoperative change. 
PORTABLE AP CHEST FILM:  The heart size is normal.  Mediastinal and hilar contours are unchanged.  There is stable-appearing left pleural effusion. There are stable-appearing bilateral interstitial opacities.  There has been interval placement of a Y stent within the trachea which demonstrates normal anatomical configuration with no definite evidence of malpositioning. There is slight improved of lung aeration bilaterally. 
IMPRESSION: 1.  Unchanged left small pleural effusion. 2.  Unchanged bilateral interstitial opacities likely representing component of pulmonary edema superimposed on pre-existing fibrotic apical changes. . 3.  Interval placement of trachea Y stent with no definite evidence of malpositioning. 4.  Slight improved aeration of the upper lobes bilaterally.

HISTORY:  55 year old female with epidural abscess at L3-4. 
RADIOLOGISTS:  Drs. [**Last Name (STitle) 6776**] and [**Name5 (PTitle) 91**], the Attending Radiologist, present and supervising the entire procedure. 
Informed consent was obtained after explaining the risks, indications, and alternative  management. 
The patient was brought to the fluoroscopic suite and placed on the table in the prone position.
